<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="58" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1184,1559]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,280,1184,1210]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Elongate setae present on the posterior surface of fore tibia. The front basitarsus of the males is curved and the face is distinctly concave. The spoon is as long as the third tarsal segments, nearly as wide and distinctly concave. The coloration of the species is very light. The wings are subhyaline (see 
<figureCitation box="[1306,1377,1262,1288]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,255,1968,1992]" captionTargetBox="[429,1167,197,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[417,1172,197,1943]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Wings of selected species a) D. atroscutellata, b) D. sordidapex, c) D. conformis, d) D. dasycnemia, and e) D. waddingtoni." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/185616/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="58">
Fig. 
<number box="[1363,1377,1262,1288]" pageId="5" pageNumber="58" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
e for example).
</paragraph>
